The Cause went soundingSOUNDING [Criticism—canonical] [Style—pun] Hennig Cohen identifies “sounding” as one of several nautical puns in lines 45-46. “Sounding,”  according to Cohen, can refer to “measuring depth for the purpose of safe navigation” but also “dropping down abruptly, and as a whaling term connotes uncertainty and suspense over when or whether the whale will surface” (Cohen 234). 
(Leslie McAbee), groped its way;
The leadsmenLEADSMAN [Criticism—canonical] [Style—pun] In lines 45-46, Hennig Cohen suggests that Melville offers several nautically-themed puns. As one of them, “leadsman” is someone who “takes soundings or measurements of depth with a lead-weighted line.” However, Cohen contends that the primary meaning for this line is of “a person who leads.” Cohen adds that this signification “is re-enforced by the fact that (leadsman) is a variant of (lodesman), meaning leader, guide, pilot or steersman (N.E.D.) (234).  
(Leslie McAbee) quarrelled in the bayIN THE BAY [Criticism—canonical] [Style] Hennig Cohen identifies this phrase as one of three nautical puns in lines 45-46. This phrase of course “refers to a body of water and to the state of being held in check, at bay” (234). 

